{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"846"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/846"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.24,0.59,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103075"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85539"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"3376"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35224"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103075"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up after a routine endoscopy as part of a Barrett\u0027s oesophagus surveillance program. She initially presented with heartburn which is now well controlled with esomeprazole, and she has not experienced any other gastrointestinal symptoms. She has no significant medical history apart from gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her only regular medication is esomeprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The endoscopy confirms the presence of a 3 cm long segment of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus with a single 5 mm area of irregularity with nodularity. Four-quadrant biopsies are performed. The histopathology report shows high grade dysplasia in the irregular area. There is no evidence of oesophagitis or hiatus hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoscopic review in three months","Radiofrequency ablation","Endoscopic mucosal resection","Increase dosage of esomeprazole","Triple therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHigh grade dysplastic tissue can be difficult to distinguish from in-situ carcinoma and once identified must be actively treated. With the advances in endoscopic therapies, the current approach involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic mucosal resection\u003C/strong\u003E (EMR) of the abnormal region and careful histological assessment of the resected tissues. This approach is all the more important if there are raised, irregular or nodular areas of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. Radiofrequency ablation (RFA) may be used in combination with endoscopic resection, but only in dealing with non-nodular areas of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. Further management will depend on accurate tumour (T) staging and possible use of endoscopic ultrasonography to assess local lymph node (N) status. For high grade dysplasia alone, patients can be kept under endoscopic surveillance and where feasible, the entire segment of Barrett\u0027s epithelium removed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic review in three months\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate management for high grade dysplasia, which requires active intervention rather than observation due to the significant risk of progression to invasive adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiofrequency ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for flat areas of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus with dysplasia, but is not appropriate as the primary intervention for nodular areas. These nodular regions should first undergo EMR to exclude invasive carcinoma before considering ablative therapies for any remaining Barrett\u0027s epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease dosage of esomeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the high grade dysplasia. While proton pump inhibitors are important for controlling reflux symptoms and may reduce inflammation, they do not reverse dysplastic changes or prevent progression to adenocarcinoma in patients with established high grade dysplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriple therapy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the combination of a proton pump inhibitor with two antibiotics for Helicobacter pylori eradication. This treatment has no role in the management of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus with high grade dysplasia, as H. pylori infection is not implicated in the pathogenesis of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus or its progression to dysplasia and cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endoscopic mucosal resection is the preferred approach for the assessment of an area of nodularity in a region of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus.","High grade dysplasia in Barrett\u0027s oesophagus requires active treatment to prevent progression to adenocarcinoma.","Radiofrequency ablation is appropriate for flat areas of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus but not for nodular regions."],"references":["Wani S, Qumseya B, Sultan S, et al. Endoscopic eradication therapy for patients with Barrett\u0027s esophagus-associated dysplasia and intramucosal cancer. Gastrointest Endoscopy 2018; 87:907-32. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29397943/","Whiteman D. C., Kendall B. J. Barrett\u0027s oesophagus: epidemiology, diagnosis and clinical management. Medical Journal of Australia. 2016;205(7):317-324. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27681974/","Garud SS, Keilin S, Cai Q, Willingham FF. Diagnosis and management of Barrett\u0027s esophagus for the endoscopist.\u00a0Therap Adv Gastroenterol. 2010;3(4):227-238. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21180605/","Grimm JC, Valero V 3rd, Molena D. Surgical indications and optimization of patients for resectable esophageal malignancies. J Thorac Dis. 2014;6(3):249-257. doi:10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2013.11.18 Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3949183/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85539"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"846"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85539"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-19T08:24:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-19T08:25:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103075"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1